## Horizon Scanning

Look beyond current regulations to anticipate future requirements:

- **Proposed legislation**: Track bills through committee and floor votes
- **Regulatory agendas**: Review semi-annual agency agendas
- **Enforcement trends**: Increasing enforcement signals stricter rules ahead
- **International precedent**: Regulations in one jurisdiction often spread
- **Industry incidents**: Breaches and scandals trigger regulatory responses

## Change Detection Signals

| Signal | Strength | Response |
|--------|----------|----------|
| Final rule in official register | Definitive | Begin implementation assessment immediately |
| Proposed rule with comment period | Strong | Assess impact; prepare comment if warranted |
| Enforcement action against peer | Strong | Self-assess against cited violations |
| Legislative bill introduced | Moderate | Add to tracking; assess if it advances |
| Agency leadership speech | Moderate | Note as directional indicator |
| Media speculation | Weak | Log; do not act until corroborated |

## Alert Escalation

| Level | Trigger | Response Time |
|-------|---------|--------------|
| Critical | Final rule affecting core operations | < 24 hours |
| High | Enforcement in our sector or proposed rule with direct impact | < 48 hours |
| Medium | Guidance update or standard change | Within 1 week |
| Low | Informational, adjacent industry | Next reporting cycle |

## Common Pitfalls

- **Alert fatigue**: Classify rigorously; reserve high-priority for actionable changes; bundle informational items into digests
- **Jurisdictional blind spots**: Map all jurisdictions where the organization operates; monitor each government level
- **Monitoring without action**: Every detected change must flow into the assessment pipeline within defined response time
